    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "In section 1.2 our team implemented methods to clean the data. Missing values were inserted with the median value of the feature, outliers were replaced with the min or max value of the accepted range (e.g., an exam_score of 150 was replaced with 100 and an exan_score of -20 was replaced with 0), and duplicate entries were removed from the data set. Missing values were replaced with the median because the picture of our histogram was approximately normal. Outliers were replaced with the min and max values because a student with an exam_score of -20 can reasonably be said to have the same probability of passing the class as a student with an exam_score of 0. Vice versa is also true, a student with an exam_score of 150 can reasonably be said to have the same probability of passing the class as a student with an exam_score of 100. Duplicate entries were remove as it is highly unlikely that two individual students will study, sleep, have a prev_exam_score, and have an exam_score that are exactly the same."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Mya__rnzJgAh"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "##1.3 Feature Selection"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "8o7N_xg-rwcE"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "#1.3 Feature Selection\n",
        "sns.heatmap(train_clean.corr(), annot=True)\n",
        "#We are selecting the feature that has the highest correlation with exam score\n",
        "simple_feat = ['hours_studied']\n",
        "#Two features that have the highest correlation with exam score\n",
        "multi_feats = ['hours_studied', 'prev_exam_score']"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 542
        },
        "id": "bI4I4-lVozD9",
        "outputId": "a044834b-d212-4113-8783-21c0a96f5a3b"
